{
  "text": "The epidemiology of atypical CAP in Cambodia remains unclear due to the current lack of data. However, this information is pivotal to guide clinical practice and antimicrobial choices, as atypical pneumonia has sometimes been associated with severe clinical presentations in Thailand [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The required techniques for atypical CAP direct diagnosis are costly and not routinely available. Studies relying on indirect laboratory diagnostic methods showed that M. pneumoniae and C. pneumoniae were the most prevalent atypical pneumonia pathogens, with C. pneumoniae most frequent in adults [CITATION_3] , while M. pneumoniae was more common in children and adolescents [CITATION_4] .",
